WEBVTT

00:00:00.720 --> 00:00:04.880
I want to start this talk off with a question that you might find a little strange.

00:00:06.480 --> 00:00:14.880
We'll start off hopefully on familiar territory on the xy-plane. On the x-axis we have the true value

00:00:14.880 --> 00:00:20.959
of some outcome variable that we're trying to model, and on the y-axis we have the predictions

00:00:20.959 --> 00:00:26.559
from a machine learning model. This machine learning model is situated in some sort of

00:00:26.559 --> 00:00:34.240
factory production context where we're trying to model the weight of a vase, and the behavior that

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:39.840
we see is that for the lighter vases we tend to predict that those vases are heavier than they

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:47.599
actually are, and for the heavier vases we tend to predict that those vases aren't as heavy as they

00:00:47.599 --> 00:00:57.520
actually are. So the strange question that I have for you is, is this model fair? Maybe a yes if you

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:03.599
think this is fair, no if you think this is unfair, or a shrug if you're like, what kind of question is that?

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:13.040
I'm seeing mostly shrugs in the crowd, and I agree with you. Like this is a bad model, but I don't

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:20.400
really feel that this is unfair in any specific way. Okay, so I have a little magic trick now. I'm

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:27.199
going to change the labels on the axis ticks, and I'm going to change the title and the subtitle,

00:01:27.919 --> 00:01:30.400
and we'll see if your answer to that question changes.

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:39.120
This machine learning model is actually assessing the sale price of homes, and that assessed value

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:45.599
is used to determine the amount of property tax that a homeowner will be charged for. And so for

00:01:45.599 --> 00:01:50.720
the less expensive homes, that model tends to predict that the home is actually more expensive

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:57.120
than it actually is, and for the more expensive homes, the model thinks that the home is not

00:01:57.120 --> 00:02:07.120
actually as expensive as it is. Is this fair? I agree, this is not fair. So this is a statistical

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:13.039
behavior that we call regressivity, where the predictions from a machine learning model tend

00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:21.360
towards the mean of the outcome variable. And in that first context, we felt that that behavior,

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:29.440
that statistical behavior of regressivity, wasn't necessarily unfair. But we change the context in

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:34.240
which the model that has the same exact model parameters, the same predictions on the same

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:40.960
distribution of an outcome, and we feel that that's unfair. And so this leads us to the first

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:47.039
conclusion of three that I want to make in this talk, is that machine learning fairness isn't about

00:02:47.039 --> 00:02:53.919
mathematical measures. It's not about the newest metric you can get access to. Fairness is about

00:02:53.919 --> 00:03:00.960
our morally held beliefs. And because of that, the same model parameters can result in behavior

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:06.639
that feels totally benign when situated in one context, and deeply unjust in another.

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:18.320
In late 2022, a group of Posit employees across the organization formed a reading group to learn

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:24.960
more about machine learning fairness as a research field, and also to think through what principled

00:03:24.960 --> 00:03:31.600
tooling for machine learning fairness looks like. A few months ago, I'm proud to say that

00:03:31.600 --> 00:03:37.520
we released some functionality that we feel helps people to analyze models with fairness in mind.

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:41.199
But I don't want to talk about that functionality today. I want to talk about

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:46.639
sort of three important things that we came out of that reading group having learned,

00:03:46.639 --> 00:03:51.440
and that we would want you to keep in mind if you're also analyzing your machine learning models

00:03:52.160 --> 00:04:00.880
with respect to fairness. To do so, we'll use this case study of tax assessment.

00:04:01.839 --> 00:04:05.839
This was sort of inspired by a talk at Posit Conference last year

00:04:05.839 --> 00:04:09.520
from folks at the Cook County Assessor's Office in Chicago.

00:04:11.279 --> 00:04:18.160
This is one news story of many about the property tax system in Chicago.

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:23.359
This reads, Cook County failed to value homes accurately for years,

00:04:23.359 --> 00:04:27.040
and the result is a property tax system that harmed the poor and helped the rich.

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:34.720
This is one of many articles about this system in Chicago, but you can find similar articles

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:41.040
about any major city in North America. And the New York Times even recently published

00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:47.600
a meta-analysis that does a similar sort of graph for cities across North America.

00:04:48.959 --> 00:04:56.000
So, the second hard part about machine learning fairness is defining what it actually is.

00:04:56.959 --> 00:05:00.559
And to demonstrate that, we'll return to this example that I showed you earlier.

00:05:01.839 --> 00:05:07.040
So, I said earlier that this is a bad model, and I'll give you that. And so, maybe our first

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:13.119
reflex to make this model act more fairly is to make it act more performant by our usual

00:05:13.519 --> 00:05:17.519
metrics of model performance, like r-squared or root-mean-squared error.

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:23.519
So, our proposal now for what a fair model is,

00:05:23.519 --> 00:05:27.359
is a model that's good by other usual measures of performance.

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:35.519
Because those errors are super-correlated, we can apply calibration, and if we're lucky,

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:41.119
we end up with predictions that look like this, where we have a fair model,

00:05:41.119 --> 00:05:46.320
predictions that look like this, where errors are independently and identically distributed,

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:52.399
meaning that their mean invariance is the same across the distribution of that true outcome

00:05:52.399 --> 00:05:58.959
variable. Okay, so maybe we feel that this machine learning model is more fair than the first one we

00:05:58.959 --> 00:06:06.160
saw. Just to check that those errors are iid, we can take a look at the residuals, and it does

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:14.880
seem like that distribution is similar across the true outcome variable. But let's not forget

00:06:15.519 --> 00:06:21.679
what those units are on the y-axis. We're saying that a homeowner of a home that's $100,000

00:06:22.239 --> 00:06:29.920
is going to be subject to similar residuals as a homeowner of a home that's $500,000

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:34.399
in their absolute magnitude. So, they're just as likely to receive a residual

00:06:34.399 --> 00:06:40.720
of $50,000 plus or minus, and that error to them is probably much more impactful than it is to

00:06:40.720 --> 00:06:48.559
somebody on the other end of that distribution. So, to me, that maybe leads to a different proposal

00:06:48.559 --> 00:06:54.160
of what a fair machine learning model looks like in this context. What if the percentage

00:06:54.160 --> 00:07:00.320
of the error was similar across the distribution of true outcome values? So, we're talking about

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:06.239
a 2% to 3% difference instead of a $10,000 to $20,000 difference. We're speaking in terms of

00:07:06.239 --> 00:07:12.000
percentages rather than absolute magnitude. If we're training a model where we can adjust the

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:17.279
loss function that we're optimizing for, we might end up with a model that looks like this,

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:23.920
where the absolute magnitude of the errors are larger for the more expensive homes,

00:07:24.480 --> 00:07:32.160
but the percentage error is similar across the distribution. But if I'm a homeowner of, in this

00:07:32.160 --> 00:07:38.239
case, a $500,000 home, and suddenly I'm subjected to these $200,000 residuals that I didn't used to

00:07:38.239 --> 00:07:45.679
see, that feels pretty unfair to me. So, what we see here is that we start with these morally held

00:07:45.679 --> 00:07:51.119
beliefs about fairness, and we map them onto mathematical measures. But the fact that they're

00:07:51.119 --> 00:07:56.720
mathematical measures doesn't necessarily mean they're any more compatible with each other than

00:07:56.720 --> 00:08:05.440
our morally held beliefs are. So, defining fairness is hard. Those definitions of fairness

00:08:06.239 --> 00:08:09.440
are not mathematically or morally compatible in general.

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:18.880
A lot of software for machine learning fairness focuses on implementing as many

00:08:19.519 --> 00:08:27.440
fairness metrics as possible. What I want to emphasize here is that machine learning

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:32.799
metrics or fairness metrics only allow us to evaluate the behavior of a model,

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:38.320
but we need to think about the whole system that the model is situated inside of.

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:44.960
So, in this example that I was just talking about, how would these predictions of what the sale price

00:08:44.960 --> 00:08:52.960
of a home would be actually be used? One tax system, I propose that you just take that assessed

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:58.799
value for the sale price of the home and multiply it by a fixed percentage, and that's the property

00:08:58.799 --> 00:09:06.719
tax that you pay. And to me, the most fair model that we've proposed so far under that system

00:09:06.719 --> 00:09:10.239
is one where we have a similar percentage error across the distribution.

00:09:11.119 --> 00:09:16.640
Where I live in Chicago, we call this the homeowner exemption, where if you live in the home

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:22.559
that you own, you start with that assessed value and you subtract off some constant number,

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:30.239
and then the results of that calculation is then multiplied by that fixed percentage,

00:09:30.239 --> 00:09:35.119
and that's the property tax that you pay. So, if we think back to that graph, we're sort of

00:09:35.679 --> 00:09:42.559
mean shifting the errors down such that the owner of an $100,000 house is not as likely to experience

00:09:42.559 --> 00:09:49.919
that very positive residual or the overvaluation of their home. If I am the owner of many $100,000

00:09:49.919 --> 00:09:57.039
homes, I'm not allowed or allotted this exemption, but the errors are sort of averaged across the

00:09:57.039 --> 00:10:03.119
homes that I own, and so everybody ends up with a similar error on that end of the distribution.

00:10:05.119 --> 00:10:10.239
So, in that case, a model that's trained with a usual performance metric like R squared or

00:10:10.239 --> 00:10:18.080
root mean squared error, that feels fine to me. But even if I could predict the sale price to the

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:27.119
dollar, if last year my valuation was half of what it is this year, even though this year it's right

00:10:27.119 --> 00:10:33.440
on the dot, is that change in the assessed value unfair in itself? Because I wasn't expecting

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:41.200
evaluation that high. So, these are all things that if we measured only with fairness metrics,

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:48.320
we wouldn't be factoring in other components of this machine learning system that trigger

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:53.039
this gut reaction that we have that reflects our morally held beliefs.

00:10:57.760 --> 00:11:01.840
Metrics evaluate the model, but the model is one part of a larger system.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:11.599
So, those are the three big hard parts that I wanted to underscore in this talk. And the last

00:11:11.599 --> 00:11:15.919
thing that I'll leave you with is that I would encourage you to choose tools that support

00:11:15.919 --> 00:11:22.640
thinking about the hard parts. If you're a tidy models user and you saw there were only a couple

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:29.679
newly exported functions that came along with this release of fairness metrics in the tidy models,

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:36.479
that's because we allotted a lot of energy to really good documentation that situates these

00:11:36.479 --> 00:11:41.760
metrics in contexts that are similar to the ones that you might see in your organization.

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:48.320
And also because those tools are minimal but flexible and they encourage you to think about

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:54.559
how that metric is situated inside of a whole system. So, if you're interested in learning more

00:11:55.119 --> 00:12:00.080
about how to use these metrics in the tidy models, the first place I would point you to

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:03.760
is these two applied articles that we put together on tidymodels.org.

00:12:04.640 --> 00:12:16.159
One analyzes a problem of GPT detectors across the difference of performance metrics between people

00:12:16.159 --> 00:12:23.119
who speak and write English natively and those that don't. In another applied analysis,

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:30.559
analyzes a machine learning model that predicts whether a patient will be readmitted to a hospital

00:12:30.559 --> 00:12:37.520
after an inpatient stay based on racial groupings. So, if you're interested in reading those articles,

00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:42.159
if you're interested in checking out the source code for this talk, or if you want to check out

00:12:42.159 --> 00:12:48.479
the sources that I've cited throughout, you can see this GitHub repository, github.com.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:57.440
While folks take a moment to write that down, I just want to say I'm very grateful

00:12:57.440 --> 00:13:02.239
to be here. And I would encourage you to track me down and ask for some hex stickers.

00:13:11.679 --> 00:13:16.640
Thank you, Simon. And a reminder to submit any questions via Slido. We're getting a couple in

00:13:16.640 --> 00:13:22.960
so far. Expect a few more to trickle in. But first, the word fair implies a moral capability

00:13:22.960 --> 00:13:27.679
that doesn't exist in tools like machine learning, no more than any other tool as the moral faculty.

00:13:27.679 --> 00:13:32.719
You seem to equate inaccuracy with unfairness, so why not simply call it inaccuracy?

00:13:32.719 --> 00:13:37.039
Would overcharging higher-priced houses somehow be fair inaccuracy?

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:44.960
This is exactly the question, right? It is very, very difficult to map our morally held beliefs

00:13:44.960 --> 00:13:50.320
about what fairness is into mathematical measures. And so, like you're saying,

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:54.880
it's important to forefront that difference between what our morally held beliefs are

00:13:54.880 --> 00:13:56.799
and what we're actually able to measure.

00:13:59.359 --> 00:14:02.559
So given how difficult it is to define ML model fairness in general,

00:14:02.559 --> 00:14:07.119
why do you think so many people are interested in evaluating if models are fair? Is it about

00:14:07.119 --> 00:14:11.119
governance, like who's on the hook if it hurts a specific group of people, or something else?

00:14:12.080 --> 00:14:18.320
I mean, I would hope that all of us don't want to cause differential harm to different groups

00:14:18.320 --> 00:14:23.919
of people through our work in machine learning. And the thought that there might be tools that

00:14:23.919 --> 00:14:28.559
allow us to adjust for that disparate harm is tempting.

00:14:30.559 --> 00:14:34.880
Is it appropriate to use LLMs for tax assessments? Do they perform better than

00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:36.000
human tax assessors?

00:14:36.960 --> 00:14:40.159
I'm not qualified to answer that question, I think.

00:14:43.679 --> 00:14:47.760
So we'll maybe get a few more questions in, but I have one in the meantime. How would you

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:52.559
maybe give advice to a data scientist who's trying to consider all the angles of fairness?

00:14:52.559 --> 00:14:55.760
I mean, obviously, domain expertise is a big piece of that, but are there

00:14:55.760 --> 00:14:58.719
any data explorations or other tips that you'd give them?

00:14:59.359 --> 00:15:05.359
Yeah, I got a similar question to a different but similar talk recently that was like,

00:15:05.440 --> 00:15:11.119
how do I talk about this with somebody without just diving into residuals and

00:15:11.119 --> 00:15:13.119
talking about loss functions and things like that?

00:15:15.119 --> 00:15:20.479
The structure of this talk, I think, aims to answer that question where we start with

00:15:20.479 --> 00:15:26.799
what our beliefs are. We start with who the stakeholders are in our problem and the

00:15:26.799 --> 00:15:35.119
potential ways that we might harm them. And that is what can help guide the analyses that we think

00:15:35.119 --> 00:15:37.440
through and the tools that we use to do so.

00:15:39.520 --> 00:15:43.440
Do you think it's better to try to correct for fairness by changing the machine learning

00:15:43.440 --> 00:15:45.840
objective function or some sort of post hoc adjustments?

00:15:47.599 --> 00:15:54.640
Both can be valuable tools. There's all sorts of machinery out there that aims not to just

00:15:54.640 --> 00:16:00.320
measure the degree of unfairness, but to somehow mitigate it. That's not currently part of

00:16:00.320 --> 00:16:04.080
the tool set that we've put together. But if you're interested in that being part of

00:16:04.080 --> 00:16:09.440
the tidy models, definitely give us a holler on the GitHub repositories and we'd be

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:10.960
interested to start that conversation.

00:16:12.479 --> 00:16:12.799
Great.

00:16:13.599 --> 00:16:18.799
Going rapid fire with you here. Do you evaluate fairness in both the training and testing

00:16:18.799 --> 00:16:20.559
data or just in the testing data?

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:26.880
You would evaluate fairness wherever it is that you're evaluating a machine learning

00:16:26.880 --> 00:16:32.320
model elsewhere. So for the assessment set, when you're resampling, the assessment set

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:38.799
would allow you to choose a model that you propose that is most fair. And then you can

00:16:38.799 --> 00:16:44.640
evaluate the final degree of unfairness, if you will, based on a given metric using the

00:16:44.640 --> 00:16:45.119
test set.

00:16:46.960 --> 00:16:51.280
This one I think follows along in that lines. But what about fairness and data annotation

00:16:51.280 --> 00:16:53.679
as they become larger sources of truth for models?

00:16:54.880 --> 00:17:01.359
Okay, yeah. So data annotation would be like the act of seeing some complexity in the world

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:02.799
and putting a label on it.

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:10.319
And I think that is the root of many evils in terms of our ability to measure the behavior

00:17:10.319 --> 00:17:15.760
of models, where there are many different ways to choose to group people. And those

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:21.119
are very much impactful for our understanding of the world and our understanding of how

00:17:21.119 --> 00:17:23.920
machine learning models simplify our understanding.

00:17:26.239 --> 00:17:30.880
Does desiring fairness and models suggest we should prefer to use simpler, more interpretable

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:33.839
models or more complex, less interpretable models?

00:17:37.599 --> 00:17:40.880
That's an interesting question. I mean, the first thing that comes to mind is like,

00:17:42.479 --> 00:17:46.880
if a more interpretable model is one that allows you to communicate more effectively

00:17:46.880 --> 00:17:52.640
to stakeholders about the implications for fairness, then maybe a model that isn't

00:17:52.640 --> 00:17:59.280
necessarily the optimum with respect to a given fairness metric could still be the most

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:00.400
fair for that situation.

00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:06.239
I'll add on to that one. Are there any tools in some more complex models that might help

00:18:06.239 --> 00:18:11.760
to open up that black box and explore levels of fairness or any sort of unexpected relationships

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:13.040
that may be occurring in the data?

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:22.560
Yeah, so in terms of interpretability, the same interpretability tools would work for

00:18:22.560 --> 00:18:28.319
models regardless of whether you're analyzing them with fairness metrics or with typical

00:18:28.319 --> 00:18:29.599
model performance metrics.

00:18:32.719 --> 00:18:33.219
Yeah.

00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:40.000
I agree. Does it make sense to look at fairness drift just as we do accuracy?

00:18:40.959 --> 00:18:42.400
Absolutely. It does.

00:18:43.040 --> 00:18:44.160
How would you recommend doing that?

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:55.280
So the vetiver set of tools for MLOps that the Piting Models team does their best to

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:57.359
integrate with. I see Julia here in the crowd.

00:18:59.119 --> 00:19:03.520
Fairness metrics in Tidy Models are metrics just like any other.

00:19:03.520 --> 00:19:08.079
We did our best to make them walk and talk like any metric from Yardstick.

00:19:09.439 --> 00:19:15.040
Maybe I shouldn't say this out loud, but if it works for a Yardstick metric, then it works

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:16.400
for a fairness metric.

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:24.479
And any tools in vetiver that can measure data drift and metric drift can also do so

00:19:24.479 --> 00:19:25.520
for fairness metrics.

00:19:26.560 --> 00:19:27.280
It's great to know.

00:19:30.239 --> 00:19:31.599
And it just reordered on me.

00:19:32.239 --> 00:19:35.119
I think we're at time anyway, so I will cut it off there.

00:19:35.119 --> 00:19:35.439
Thank you.

00:19:35.439 --> 00:19:42.959
Thank you.

